    'title' => 'La surconsommation',
    'body' => '<p>I recently watched this video:</p><p><iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/57126054" width="640" height="360" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This really got me thinking. It&#39;s entitled &quot;La&nbsp;surconsommation&quot; which translates from French&nbsp;as &quot;Overconsumption&quot;. The video itself is touching to say the least, you see what happens to nature at the hands of our species, how we have claimed dominance over all other creatures&nbsp;on this planet&nbsp;and use them as we see fit.</p><p>What I found more interesting, however, were the reactions to this video. In the comments, and on the internet in general, the reaction appears to be mixed. It&#39;s rare that you&#39;ll find a level headed response to this video.&nbsp;You have people going to extremes on both sides of the spectrum, some reacting in sheer horror, damning our species for surviving, and some reacting with crass humour, likely to self-assure themselves that it&#39;s not their fault.&nbsp;</p><p>But is it their&nbsp;(and our) fault? Do we overconsume? Should humanity as a species blame itself for simply surviving?&nbsp;</p><p>I sometimes get accused of over thinking, contemplating a little too much and perhaps coming off as a little cold and clinical with my opinions, however what this video highlighted for me was exactly how efficient humanity has become at surviving. It&#39;s this bare faced ruthless efficiency which most people are shocked by the most, the fact that we have this &#39;food&#39; and we farm it in such a way so that people don&#39;t go hungry.</p><p>However, we&#39;re obviously not efficient enough at this yet, or the efficiency is off-balance, favoring one side of the world and not another. There were comments on the video where it was said that &quot;people in the middle ages lived better&quot;. It&#39;s a nice thought, to think of every man owning his own farm, with his own cattle and livestock, his own vegetable patch. It&#39;s quaint. H<span style="line-height:1.6em">owever we have people living in middle ages conditions and starving in third world countries while the first world is ruthlessly efficient at surviving. Not so quaint.</span></p><p>I think that the end of the video serves only to highlight the overconsumption of the first world - with the McDonalds scene and the surgeon marking up the obese man for a procedure. The rest of it for me simply highlighted how ruthlessly efficient humanity has become at surviving. I do think that humanity as a species will have to get even better at this if we want to keep everyone in the world fed. The first / third world divide will take more of the same as is pictured in this video to bridge, unfortunately.</p>',

    'title_seo' => 'la-surconsommation',
    'share_id' => '5d6n',
    'comments' => '1',
    'views' => 1,
